00:54.721 --> 00:56.427
(WIND WHISTLING)

00:56.515 --> 00:59.097
<i>The Arctic ice guards a secret.</i>

01:02.771 --> 01:06.935
<i>Bleak and barren as it seems, it stirs with life.</i>

01:08.026 --> 01:09.266
(CHIRPS)

01:10.445 --> 01:11.480
(BARKING)

01:11.572 --> 01:13.858
<i>Just look a little deeper.</i>

01:25.836 --> 01:27.076
(GROWLS)

01:27.379 --> 01:31.839
<i>To last the year,
the ice bear needs to eat 40 seals.</i>

01:33.510 --> 01:36.001
<i>One more is all it'll take.</i>

01:37.806 --> 01:39.717
<i>Spring is almost over.</i>

01:40.601 --> 01:44.389
<i>If he doesn't catch this one,
he may not survive.</i>

01:46.023 --> 01:47.388
(GROWLING)

01:47.691 --> 01:48.851
(SEAL BARKING)

01:49.985 --> 01:51.395
(SPLASHING)

02:00.120 --> 02:01.326
(GRUNTS)

02:01.788 --> 02:04.370
<i>That may be his death knell.</i>

02:07.711 --> 02:09.997
<i>He can 't hunt seals without the ice.</i>

02:10.380 --> 02:11.620
(GRUNTS)

02:14.301 --> 02:18.135
<i>Now the ice is about to disappear.</i>

02:18.347 --> 02:19.757
(RUMBLING)

02:24.895 --> 02:26.180
<i>It's late June.</i>

02:33.570 --> 02:37.108
<i>A few generations ago,
the ice bear would have had another month</i>

02:37.866 --> 02:41.108
<i>before he ran out of time
to make his quota of seals.</i>

02:43.246 --> 02:47.990
<i>But, this year, his world is shrinking early.</i>

02:49.878 --> 02:51.209
(SQUEALING)

03:02.516 --> 03:04.177
<i>He 's got no choice.</i>

03:05.977 --> 03:08.218
<i>He has to enter a new world</i>

03:10.732 --> 03:12.723
<i>of danger.</i>

03:27.290 --> 03:28.655
(GRUNTING)

03:36.591 --> 03:39.833
<i>Ice Bear is three years old.</i>

03:40.929 --> 03:43.466
<i>Just a teen by polar bear standards.</i>

03:48.019 --> 03:50.476
<i>Now he's got to somehow make it to shore</i>

03:52.357 --> 03:56.270
<i>almost 500 gruelling kilometres away.</i>

03:58.905 --> 04:03.023
<i>He 's done it before, guided by his mother.</i>

04:03.118 --> 04:04.904
<i>Now he 's on his own</i>

04:05.996 --> 04:11.161
<i>and it's going to be one of the longest,
cruelest summers on record.</i>

04:15.464 --> 04:19.423
<i>He 's one of 2, 000 bears
who live in Canada 's Hudson Bay.</i>

04:20.761 --> 04:24.720
<i>Every year, when the ice melts,
some have to head south.</i>

04:26.266 --> 04:28.632
<i>First to islands along their way,</i>

04:30.228 --> 04:32.014
<i>then to the mainland.</i>

04:37.569 --> 04:42.780
<i>Ice Bear and his community live farther south
than any other polar bears on the planet.</i>

04:46.787 --> 04:52.623
<i>For generations, they've been the only group
forced to survive off the ice all summer.</i>

04:55.670 --> 04:57.080
<i>If the world keeps warming,</i>

04:58.089 --> 05:00.296
<i>they won 't be alone.</i>

05:04.012 --> 05:07.800
<i>Polar bears around the world
may also be exiled,</i>

05:07.891 --> 05:11.349
<i>and face the same life-or-death struggle.</i>

05:12.938 --> 05:14.769
(SNORTING)

05:17.234 --> 05:18.599
(GROWLING)

05:19.027 --> 05:20.608
<i>All across Hudson Bay,</i>

05:21.029 --> 05:23.987
<i>marine mammals are looking
for summer homes.</i>

05:30.872 --> 05:35.411
<i>Walruses, a tempting source of fat.</i>

05:39.047 --> 05:43.416
<i>Ice Bear can pick up a scent
almost a kilometre away.</i>

05:48.515 --> 05:49.800
(SNIFFING)

05:49.891 --> 05:53.008
<i>This may be his one chance to make up</i>

05:53.228 --> 05:56.391
<i>for that seal he missed before the ice melted.</i>

05:56.898 --> 05:58.229
(GRUNTING)

06:02.696 --> 06:05.563
<i>The walrus' nose is keen, too.</i>

06:16.751 --> 06:18.912
<i>The mothers' guards go up.</i>

06:22.591 --> 06:26.379
<i>Ice Bear is taking on a creature
who 's adept in the water.</i>

06:26.970 --> 06:30.337
<i>A ton of tusk and trouble.</i>

06:39.691 --> 06:41.898
<i>It is a remarkable encounter.</i>

06:45.113 --> 06:47.104
<i>A scene rarely witnessed.</i>

07:01.171 --> 07:02.627
(GRUNTING)

07:08.094 --> 07:11.461
<i>Being on his own for the first time
is harrowing.</i>

07:13.892 --> 07:16.679
<i>One in five adolescent bears die.</i>

07:25.695 --> 07:30.564
<i>For cubs to survive, their mother's lessons
have to last them a lifetime.</i>

07:46.466 --> 07:48.832
<i>Cub boy, cub girl,</i>

07:48.927 --> 07:52.340
<i>neither's got much fat
for energy and insulation.</i>

08:04.526 --> 08:08.439
<i>They keep close to Mum,
mimicking her every move.</i>

08:11.616 --> 08:16.076
<i>For the first two years of her cubs' life,
they're completely dependent on her.</i>

08:37.976 --> 08:39.432
<i>They're still nursing.</i>

08:39.519 --> 08:43.477
<i>She needs to find herself food,
or her cubs won 't last.</i>

08:49.904 --> 08:52.941
<i>This desolate slab is just a pit stop.</i>

08:54.868 --> 08:55.948
<i>Though its scent</i>

08:56.077 --> 08:59.865
<i>is now forever ingrained
in her cubs' memory.</i>

09:09.382 --> 09:11.839
<i>That's what's keeping Ice Bear going now.</i>

09:12.886 --> 09:16.424
<i>His memory has led him to the same islands.</i>

09:16.598 --> 09:17.963
(CAWING)

09:22.187 --> 09:26.430
<i>The scent he's picked up?
Thick-billed murres.</i>

09:38.203 --> 09:42.071
<i>The division between sky and sea
is lost on them.</i>

09:47.629 --> 09:51.668
<i>This time of year, the plankton bloom
draws herring and shrimp,</i>

09:55.011 --> 09:56.876
<i>a feast for murres.</i>

10:13.863 --> 10:16.149
<i>The bear smells a meal, too.</i>

10:18.159 --> 10:19.365
(SNIFFS)

10:21.454 --> 10:25.993
<i>But there 's 200 metres between him and it.</i>

10:29.337 --> 10:32.704
<i>It's a challenge
no sensible adult bear would go for.</i>

10:34.259 --> 10:36.500
<i>Leave it to a desperate teen.</i>

10:38.680 --> 10:40.045
(CAWING)

11:07.709 --> 11:12.874
<i>The murres pick cliffs for their colonies
to keep predators from approaching.</i>

11:14.716 --> 11:17.002
<i>The ledges are just enough purchase.</i>

11:17.093 --> 11:18.549
(SQUAWKING)

11:20.597 --> 11:24.181
<i>Nobody expects a cliff-climbing polar bear.</i>

11:38.239 --> 11:41.948
<i>This is behaviour
never before captured on video.</i>

11:42.118 --> 11:43.733
(CAWING)

11:46.915 --> 11:48.701
(POLAR BEAR GROWLS)

11:59.552 --> 12:04.592
<i>The question is, for all the risk and work,
is it worth it?</i>

12:06.142 --> 12:07.882
<i>Not for one chick.</i>

12:08.770 --> 12:11.887
<i>Bones and feathers are a recipe
for starvation.</i>

12:12.857 --> 12:15.018
<i>Ice Bear needs fat.</i>

12:29.832 --> 12:34.166
<i>His only hope is still 250 kilometres away.</i>

12:37.006 --> 12:39.543
<i>He 's got to make it to the mainland.</i>

12:48.893 --> 12:51.475
<i>There are no landmarks to guide him.</i>

12:59.821 --> 13:04.064
<i>Incredibly, he can orient. By day, to the sun.</i>

13:15.837 --> 13:18.499
<i>By night, the stars are his compass.</i>

13:27.348 --> 13:31.011
<i>He may actually use them
to track his course ahead.</i>

13:38.192 --> 13:43.528
<i>Night after night,
Ice Bear doesn't sleep or eat.</i>

13:55.877 --> 13:57.367
(SNORTING)

14:03.092 --> 14:05.083
<i>After 1 0 days,</i>

14:08.264 --> 14:09.720
<i>land.</i>

14:14.270 --> 14:19.355
<i>But then polar bears are built to last on ice,
not land.</i>

14:40.630 --> 14:44.418
<i>For Ice Bear, survival might be a long shot.</i>

15:01.067 --> 15:05.606
<i>Ice Bear actually evolved from a land bear,
like the grizzly.</i>

15:08.741 --> 15:13.030
<i>Now he 's forced to revisit his roots,
and adapt.</i>

15:14.372 --> 15:16.112
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

15:18.626 --> 15:19.866
(GROWLS)

15:20.294 --> 15:23.206
<i>He 's not equipped to hunt this strange prey.</i>

15:25.174 --> 15:28.337
<i>Animals of the earth, not the ice.</i>

15:33.558 --> 15:35.139
(GRUNTS)

15:35.226 --> 15:36.841
(INSECT BUZZING)

15:37.895 --> 15:40.056
<i>And he's not designed for the heat.</i>

15:45.194 --> 15:49.028
<i>It's 28 degrees Celsius.</i>

15:50.158 --> 15:51.944
(HONKING)

15:54.954 --> 15:56.285
<i>Misery.</i>

15:56.747 --> 15:58.487
(INSECTS BUZZING)

16:05.756 --> 16:06.996
(GROWLING)

16:07.175 --> 16:08.665
(BUZZING)

16:16.893 --> 16:19.259
<i>At least the bugs get to eat.</i>

16:24.400 --> 16:25.685
(GROWLS)

16:35.244 --> 16:37.485
<i>There's no way to get comfortable.</i>

16:44.712 --> 16:48.705
<i>Another older male has been here
long enough to know.</i>

16:48.799 --> 16:50.005
<i>Get wet.</i>

16:50.218 --> 16:52.379
(ROARING)

16:52.845 --> 16:56.258
<i>Ice Bear has got to learn the ropes.</i>

17:00.728 --> 17:05.518
<i>That's one thing he's got going for him.
Polar bears are eager students.</i>

17:18.704 --> 17:23.743
<i>One life lesson he needs now
is how to keep from starving.</i>

17:31.759 --> 17:36.674
<i>In fact, scarfing down snacks is a mistake.</i>

17:38.266 --> 17:42.851
<i>The veteran knows that eating
would throw off the altered state he 's in.</i>

17:45.773 --> 17:52.110
<i>To get his metabolism to slow down,
the older male is fasting the whole summer.</i>

17:57.451 --> 18:01.945
<i>It's a zombie-like state
called "walking hibernation. "</i>

18:03.916 --> 18:09.161
<i>He'll live off his fat reserves
and spend his waking hours half-awake.</i>

18:15.970 --> 18:18.552
<i>But the ice bear can 't swing it.</i>

18:18.639 --> 18:21.802
<i>He 's too young to make
the metabolic change.</i>

18:23.477 --> 18:29.097
<i>He can last the length of a typical summer
before starvation sets in.</i>

18:34.530 --> 18:38.648
<i>The problem is summer has gotten longer.</i>

18:52.256 --> 18:56.499
<i>This female is already at death 's door.</i>

18:57.511 --> 19:01.470
<i>She didn't eat enough seals
before the ice broke up.</i>

19:02.850 --> 19:04.636
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

19:10.024 --> 19:13.312
<i>Drinking is a sign of desperation.</i>

19:21.577 --> 19:27.288
<i>If she were healthy, she 'd get hydrated
by metabolising her own fat.</i>

19:27.375 --> 19:29.206
<i>But she has no fat.</i>

19:56.320 --> 19:58.982
<i>It's a cruel fate.</i>

19:59.073 --> 20:03.533
<i>To come so far
just to suffer on a distant shore.</i>

20:03.703 --> 20:05.193
(INSECTS BUZZING)

20:05.287 --> 20:06.572
(EXHALES)

20:08.999 --> 20:10.990
(SCREECHING)

20:17.758 --> 20:21.751
<i>Not all Hudson Bay bears
put their trust in the land.</i>

20:25.057 --> 20:28.766
<i>It's August, and a straggler is still adrift.</i>

20:31.272 --> 20:35.436
<i>He's got a strategy to stay here
the whole season long.</i>

20:37.695 --> 20:40.186
<i>He 's learned to hunt along the way</i>

20:45.786 --> 20:48.323
<i>and take on a walrus.</i>

20:56.255 --> 21:00.794
<i>In the water,
the straggler is no match for a walrus.</i>

21:02.136 --> 21:03.216
<i>But, eventually,</i>

21:04.138 --> 21:06.595
<i>the herd needs to rest.</i>

21:10.478 --> 21:12.139
(BARKING)

21:20.362 --> 21:23.525
<i>The perfect opportunity for an ambush.</i>

21:30.498 --> 21:35.037
<i>They've been out on a four-day binge,
foraging for clams.</i>

21:35.127 --> 21:37.584
<i>Now they're exhausted.</i>

21:37.671 --> 21:39.207
(GROWLING)

21:41.050 --> 21:43.336
<i>One catch, and the straggler</i>

21:43.511 --> 21:46.753
<i>will have enough to last him for days.</i>

21:53.354 --> 21:55.936
<i>A calf's body is one-third fat.</i>

21:57.191 --> 22:00.183
<i>But the young are all surrounded by adults.</i>

22:00.361 --> 22:03.068
<i>Big, dangerous animals.</i>

22:05.991 --> 22:09.404
<i>While they're restless, their guard is up.</i>

22:10.162 --> 22:11.527
(GRUNTS)

22:19.129 --> 22:21.916
<i>There 's no such thing as one itchy walrus.</i>

22:24.760 --> 22:28.093
<i>The herd that moults together,
itches together.</i>

22:45.072 --> 22:46.608
(GRUNTS SOFTLY)

22:48.367 --> 22:49.573
<i>Finally.</i>

22:52.246 --> 22:54.487
<i>Most bears wouldn't risk it.</i>

22:57.042 --> 23:00.626
<i>The hungry straggler isn't thinking twice.</i>

23:16.020 --> 23:18.102
(GROWLING)

23:24.570 --> 23:28.358
<i>The straggler approaches downwind
to avoid detection.</i>

23:37.958 --> 23:39.698
(BARKING)

23:57.019 --> 24:01.353
<i>A mother's instinct to care for her young
is a powerful drive.</i>

24:02.441 --> 24:05.524
<i>There 's only one that can be stronger.</i>

24:08.405 --> 24:09.986
<i>Hunger.</i>

24:14.870 --> 24:16.576
(GROWLING)

24:17.998 --> 24:23.618
<i>The straggler will follow the herd all summer,
picking off calves with ease.</i>

24:31.387 --> 24:35.721
<i>He won 't need to bother
migrating to land this year.</i>

24:43.732 --> 24:46.690
<i>Some castaways aren't so lucky.</i>

24:51.156 --> 24:57.072
<i>Here, far from where the bears belong,
death is a fact of life.</i>

24:57.705 --> 24:59.036
(BUZZING)

25:06.130 --> 25:08.371
<i>He may have died from an injury.</i>

25:08.465 --> 25:12.424
<i>Or from swimming those
hundreds of kilometres to get here.</i>

25:13.846 --> 25:19.432
<i>But his misfortune may be
the starving female 's salvation.</i>

26:05.189 --> 26:08.226
<i>Cannibalism is rare among polar bears.</i>

26:09.318 --> 26:13.277
<i>Being forced to live on land
changes everything.</i>

26:21.830 --> 26:24.788
<i>On the ice, she 's a noble hunter.</i>

26:25.793 --> 26:29.911
<i>Now she 's reduced to scavenging
the flesh of her own kind.</i>

26:36.512 --> 26:40.755
<i>In 1 6 years,
the Western Hudson Bay polar bears</i>

26:40.849 --> 26:43.932
<i>have dwindled by a staggering 22%.</i>

26:48.607 --> 26:49.813
<i>This female</i>

26:50.734 --> 26:53.146
<i>probably won 't survive the season.</i>

27:03.288 --> 27:07.827
<i>For mother and cubs,
the journey is finally over.</i>

27:07.918 --> 27:10.785
<i>But the odyssey has taken a toll on her.</i>

27:16.468 --> 27:19.926
<i>Through the long journey here,
she 's had to nurse them.</i>

27:22.808 --> 27:26.926
<i>While adult males withdraw
into walking hibernation,</i>

27:28.939 --> 27:31.681
<i>her cubs depend on her being awake.</i>

27:33.694 --> 27:37.653
<i>The demands of nursing can be dire.</i>

27:37.739 --> 27:40.776
<i>Somehow, she 's got to find food.</i>

27:57.926 --> 28:01.089
<i>The ice bear seizes an opportunity,</i>

28:03.724 --> 28:05.680
<i>takes the mother's cue,</i>

28:06.560 --> 28:08.892
<i>and follows her.</i>

28:11.315 --> 28:13.852
<i>She 's guided by memory</i>

28:14.860 --> 28:20.571
<i>of an exhausting three-day walk to a cove
where she 's found food before.</i>

28:27.998 --> 28:29.738
(WIND WHISTLING)

28:36.757 --> 28:41.626
<i>Here, beluga whales rub against the rocks
and moult their skin.</i>

28:42.262 --> 28:44.093
(SINGING)

28:54.024 --> 28:57.312
<i>When the tide goes out, a few get beached.</i>

29:11.500 --> 29:14.458
<i>Mother and cubs feed first.</i>

29:14.586 --> 29:18.204
<i>Cub boy and cub girl are
beginning to get weaned,</i>

29:18.298 --> 29:20.289
<i>and what better inducement?</i>

29:21.134 --> 29:24.376
<i>Ice Bear knows to give the family wide berth.</i>

29:25.472 --> 29:27.133
(BIRD SCREECHING)

29:30.811 --> 29:32.802
<i>Some scraps tide him over</i>

29:33.897 --> 29:37.060
<i>and, rather than fight,
he's learned to conserve his energy.</i>

29:42.656 --> 29:47.070
<i>And to be patient,
though he's on the verge of starvation.</i>

30:08.682 --> 30:14.222
<i>For Ice Bear, after weeks of waiting,
it's time to eat.</i>

30:21.987 --> 30:25.104
<i>Mum isn't yet free of her burden to nurse.</i>

30:26.366 --> 30:29.529
<i>And now she 's got another problem.</i>

30:33.165 --> 30:37.704
<i>The ice bear is going to
follow her everywhere.</i>

30:37.794 --> 30:42.879
<i>For him, that could make the difference
between life and death.</i>

30:53.894 --> 30:55.725
<i>September.</i>

30:56.229 --> 30:57.890
(SQUAWKING)

30:59.775 --> 31:02.858
<i>With the fall, animals are on the move.</i>

31:10.243 --> 31:13.235
<i>But one is settling in for the long haul.</i>

31:17.918 --> 31:21.957
<i>By now, every polar bear
that's coming ashore has arrived.</i>

31:23.423 --> 31:24.538
(GRUNTS)

31:25.258 --> 31:28.216
<i>On the ice, they would've led lives apart.</i>

31:28.929 --> 31:32.296
<i>Polar bears in the high north
seldom cross paths.</i>

31:34.101 --> 31:36.467
<i>The Hudson Bay bears are different.</i>

31:37.062 --> 31:38.802
(GROWLING)

31:46.905 --> 31:50.989
<i>This time of year, they're forced
into a narrow corridor of shoreline.</i>

31:51.743 --> 31:53.028
(GROWLING)

31:53.120 --> 31:54.906
<i>They socialise.</i>

31:57.290 --> 32:00.327
<i>And Ice Bear gets to learn all the more.</i>

32:03.130 --> 32:08.295
<i>Males fight to win a mate.
These two are just sparring for practice.</i>

32:10.554 --> 32:12.135
(GROWLING CONTINUES)

32:21.523 --> 32:24.139
<i>For the cubs, it's a spectator sport.</i>

32:35.871 --> 32:38.738
<i>Being social has its advantages.</i>

32:38.832 --> 32:39.992
<i>The more practice you get,</i>

32:40.333 --> 32:43.791
<i>the better your chances
when it's time for the real fight.</i>

32:53.930 --> 32:55.386
<i>Though, when they feel crowded,</i>

32:55.932 --> 32:58.765
<i>big males are known to attack cubs.</i>

33:03.190 --> 33:08.025
<i>Nursing keeps Mother's young
from wandering off and getting into trouble.</i>

33:09.154 --> 33:12.271
<i>Unless trouble follows them.</i>

33:18.246 --> 33:22.080
<i>Ice Bear has been tailing the mother
for weeks.</i>

33:26.213 --> 33:27.623
(GRUNTING)

33:30.884 --> 33:33.546
<i>Challenging him to leave would take energy.</i>

33:36.848 --> 33:40.011
<i>But so does corralling her cubs.</i>

33:45.607 --> 33:46.813
(GRUNTS)

33:52.906 --> 33:55.773
<i>Then, a milestone.</i>

34:00.539 --> 34:02.746
<i>Boy cub draws away.</i>

34:14.553 --> 34:17.215
<i>Independence is a rite of passage.</i>

34:18.473 --> 34:20.929
<i>But Ice Bear may turn aggressive.</i>

34:23.311 --> 34:26.098
<i>Mother levels a warning.</i>

34:31.987 --> 34:33.943
(GROWLING)

34:34.697 --> 34:37.735
<i>But boy cub has tasted
something irresistible.</i>

34:38.076 --> 34:39.407
(PANTING)

34:59.389 --> 35:01.801
<i>It's a costly game of cat and mouse.</i>

35:05.687 --> 35:09.771
<i>The calories the cubs are burning
come from Mum 's milk.</i>

35:13.737 --> 35:15.853
<i>This has got to stop.</i>

35:18.116 --> 35:19.777
(GROWLING)

35:29.878 --> 35:35.248
<i>Some teenagers are a bad influence.
This one is worse.</i>

35:35.717 --> 35:37.378
(BIRDS SCREECHING)

35:38.345 --> 35:43.214
<i>A distraction that's blinded Mum
to a deadly visitor.</i>

35:47.520 --> 35:49.135
<i>A wolf.</i>

35:51.983 --> 35:55.020
<i>Where there 's one wolf,
there could be a pack.</i>

36:00.700 --> 36:02.281
(GROWLING)

36:17.467 --> 36:19.583
<i>Ice Bear is on his own.</i>

36:31.189 --> 36:34.477
<i>They're lucky the wolf is as well.</i>

36:37.153 --> 36:40.896
<i>But, in the confusion,
Ice Bear loses track of the others,</i>

36:42.075 --> 36:45.408
<i>his lifeline to food and family.</i>

36:59.175 --> 37:01.382
<i>Mother's journey isn't over.</i>

37:03.972 --> 37:07.556
<i>Here, on the coast,
they're exposed to threats.</i>

37:10.520 --> 37:14.138
<i>Perhaps there'll be safety
in the cover of the forest.</i>

37:19.070 --> 37:20.480
(SCREECHING)

37:26.035 --> 37:31.575
<i>Their exile is taking them deeper still
into a world even stranger to them.</i>

37:31.875 --> 37:33.456
(PANTING)

37:42.802 --> 37:44.588
<i>Nobody knows much about the time</i>

37:44.679 --> 37:47.637
<i>mothers and cubs spend
hidden in the woods.</i>

37:54.105 --> 37:56.312
<i>That is about to change.</i>

38:05.074 --> 38:06.484
(INAUDIBLE)

38:18.505 --> 38:21.463
<i>These aren't hunters. They're biologists.</i>

38:23.218 --> 38:26.005
<i>And their ammo is just a tranquiliser.</i>

38:29.265 --> 38:31.256
<i>They believe the Hudson Bay bears</i>

38:31.559 --> 38:37.429
<i>could be a bellwether for the entire species,
pioneers of the warming world.</i>

38:37.524 --> 38:39.230
(PANTING)

38:39.400 --> 38:43.393
<i>These bears spend so much time
on land already.</i>

38:43.488 --> 38:49.028
<i>If they can 't adapt to the longer summers,
other populations don 't stand a chance.</i>

38:51.663 --> 38:54.154
<i>They fit Mum with a video camera.</i>

39:10.849 --> 39:15.684
<i>As she wakes up,
a unique home movie begins rolling.</i>

39:18.815 --> 39:22.307
<i>In two weeks, the camera will pop off</i>

39:22.402 --> 39:25.485
<i>and the researchers can
get their first glimpse</i>

39:25.572 --> 39:28.860
<i>from a polar bear's point of view.</i>

39:30.326 --> 39:34.114
<i>It offers a remarkable revelation.</i>

39:34.205 --> 39:38.118
<i>The bears have a sweet tooth for berries.</i>

39:40.587 --> 39:42.543
<i>It makes no sense.</i>

39:45.717 --> 39:50.427
<i>Berries have no fat,
no apparent nutritional value for them.</i>

39:51.472 --> 39:53.929
<i>And foraging takes a lot of energy.</i>

39:59.105 --> 40:01.221
<i>Maybe it's a throwback.</i>

40:01.316 --> 40:05.400
<i>Terrestrial bears, like grizzlies,
are big on berries.</i>

40:06.446 --> 40:11.941
<i>Living on land may be driving the polar bears
to revert to their evolutionary roots.</i>

40:14.370 --> 40:16.361
<i>A desperate strategy.</i>

40:23.838 --> 40:25.829
<i>November.</i>

40:31.304 --> 40:35.593
<i>Just a generation ago, Hudson Bay
would have been frozen by now.</i>

40:41.356 --> 40:44.940
<i>Ice Bear's first summer alone should be over,</i>

40:45.985 --> 40:49.477
<i>but he 's trapped on land in limbo.</i>

40:56.996 --> 41:00.238
<i>Following his instincts, he heads northwest,</i>

41:00.333 --> 41:02.665
<i>where the sea freezes earliest.</i>

41:08.591 --> 41:10.832
<i>The snow along his way is just a tease.</i>

41:13.012 --> 41:14.172
(GRUNTS)

41:15.264 --> 41:16.845
(DISTANT GROWLING)

41:17.266 --> 41:18.847
(GRUNTING)

41:19.143 --> 41:20.804
<i>He's not alone.</i>

41:22.230 --> 41:24.095
(ROARING)

41:52.593 --> 41:54.174
<i>By this point in the season,</i>

41:54.262 --> 41:58.221
<i>sparring partners have squared off
many times in mock battles.</i>

42:01.060 --> 42:03.392
<i>They've come to know who's their measure,</i>

42:03.896 --> 42:05.181
<i>who 's a menace,</i>

42:05.565 --> 42:07.897
<i>and when it's time to walk away.</i>

42:13.573 --> 42:17.065
<i>If Ice Bear is going to someday
compete for a mate,</i>

42:17.368 --> 42:20.826
<i>he 's got to find someone his own size
to spar with.</i>

42:28.337 --> 42:29.918
(GROWLS WEARILY)

42:35.428 --> 42:39.467
<i>He 's searched for food, for haven,
for company,</i>

42:40.058 --> 42:41.468
<i>in vain.</i>

42:42.560 --> 42:46.178
<i>Now the season delivers the ultimate insult.</i>

43:12.131 --> 43:15.794
<i>The route he follows was blazed
thousands of years ago.</i>

43:19.764 --> 43:22.301
<i>Before tourists,</i>

43:25.353 --> 43:27.344
<i>before cameras,</i>

43:28.189 --> 43:29.804
(CAMERAS CLICKING)

43:30.316 --> 43:33.729
<i>before the summer got so damned long.</i>

43:40.451 --> 43:42.066
<i>He 's curious, too.</i>

43:42.578 --> 43:45.035
<i>He gets to visit the human zoo.</i>

43:56.050 --> 43:57.961
<i>Business is booming.</i>

43:58.427 --> 44:00.964
<i>The tourist season lasts longer than ever,</i>

44:01.055 --> 44:04.092
<i>since the bears are stuck here
an extra month.</i>

44:13.860 --> 44:17.944
<i>Polar bears are crossing paths
with our world more and more.</i>

44:19.866 --> 44:21.822
<i>The encounter can get ugly.</i>

44:21.951 --> 44:23.407
(BARKING)

44:29.584 --> 44:31.324
<i>Dogs, like wolves,</i>

44:31.878 --> 44:34.369
<i>are ancient enemies of bears.</i>

44:35.047 --> 44:39.256
<i>But, this time, it's the pack that's at risk.</i>

44:39.343 --> 44:40.833
(BARKING)

44:41.053 --> 44:45.547
<i>The bear that's approaching
could not be more hungry.</i>

44:47.643 --> 44:48.974
(GRUNTING)

44:56.652 --> 44:58.233
(BARKING)

45:01.407 --> 45:04.149
<i>The ice bear could easily kill a dog.</i>

45:17.548 --> 45:20.915
<i>Instead, an extraordinary turn.</i>

45:26.599 --> 45:30.012
<i>That a bear wants companionship with dogs</i>

45:30.144 --> 45:32.510
<i>is a strange sign of the times.</i>

45:39.028 --> 45:42.395
<i>No less bizarre than that
he would need to wait for winter,</i>

45:43.574 --> 45:45.735
<i>so long overdue.</i>

45:55.127 --> 45:56.788
(BARKING)

46:01.425 --> 46:05.134
<i>For the ice bear,
company may be a consolation,</i>

46:07.139 --> 46:08.595
<i>but it's not the answer.</i>

46:23.155 --> 46:25.146
(YAWNING)

46:30.997 --> 46:32.407
(BARKING)

46:41.674 --> 46:45.667
<i>The ice is finally beginning to beckon.</i>

46:52.935 --> 46:56.018
<i>Come December, the waters roil.</i>

47:06.032 --> 47:10.071
<i>On the banks of Hudson Bay,
the weary gather.</i>

47:14.665 --> 47:18.704
<i>The ice bear has finally found his way
to others his age.</i>

47:20.046 --> 47:21.502
(GROWLING)

47:24.091 --> 47:28.676
<i>If they're going to compete for females,
they have to learn to spar</i>

47:29.722 --> 47:32.555
<i>and this is their last fleeting chance.</i>

47:50.785 --> 47:54.573
<i>A chance Ice Bear now seizes.</i>

48:30.282 --> 48:32.944
<i>A bond and rivalry forged on land</i>

48:33.911 --> 48:36.493
<i>may last them years on the ice.</i>

48:55.808 --> 48:59.676
<i>Finally, the sea turns from black to white.</i>

49:07.445 --> 49:11.029
<i>He 's survived one of the
longest summers on record.</i>

49:11.866 --> 49:14.949
<i>Nearly six months on land.</i>

49:21.542 --> 49:25.330
<i>His homecoming is a bay
once again entombed.</i>

49:27.965 --> 49:31.002
<i>Next year,
the summer may be longer than ever.</i>

49:32.553 --> 49:36.796
<i>The time to hunt seals on ice
may get even shorter.</i>

49:39.768 --> 49:44.387
<i>But, for now, the ice bear is home.</i>

